title: [react-native]: Add global declarations for RN polyfills
body:
This change adds specific definitions for the global objects and functions implemented by React Native. It allows project using these type declarations to compile successfully while excluding the TypeScript "DOM" libraries. In other words, the compiler settings in `tsconfig.json` can specify `ES2017` instead of `ES6`. The problem with `ES6` (and other libs that include the DOM) is that they (1) pollute the global namespace with many objects that don't exist (e.g. `screen`) and (2) they have incorrect definitions for shared objects (e.g. `console.assert()` is not implemented in React Native).

By defining globals in this type declaration, the developer can now target a more accurate runtime environment.

The only missing piece now is the definitions for `XMLHttpRequest` and `fetch`.

- [pathwatcher](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/tree/master/types/pathwatcher) (@vvakame)

- [atom-keymap](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/tree/master/types/atom-keymap) (@enlight)
- [event-kit](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/tree/master/types/event-kit) (@enlight)
- [first-mate](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/tree/master/types/first-mate) (@enlight)

- [status-bar](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/tree/master/types/status-bar) (@vvakame)

The issues fixed by this pull request are:
- #4482
- #5372

The type definitions for the [Atom Text Editor](https://atom.io/) API have been severely out of date for well over a year now, with this pull request providing a replacement for them. Atom has five primary submodules, each of which had to be either substantially modified or replaced as well in order to provide this update. I've taken this opportunity to enforce a consistent style across the six modules, with tslint configuration files being added as well.

These definitions are still a work in progress, though the public API has been fully implemented. The common mistakes couldn't be avoided everywhere due to the size of the definitions, but I do plan to work on ridding the definitions of them over time.

title: [react-intl] Allow booleans and dates when formatting a message
body:
This is the same change that I did previously in https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/17133, but for react-intl's React components instead of the injectable methods.

Currently only strings and numbers are allowed as values when using react-intl's `<FormattedMessage>` and `<FormattedHTMLMessage>` components.

react-intl's API Wiki defines the value for values property as object (https://github.com/yahoo/react-intl/wiki/Components#formattedmessage), which means that you should be able to pass the method any kind of data inside of an object.

Using object seems to be banned by tslint in this project, so changed the code to allow `boolean`, `Date`, `number` and `string` as usable values.

title: [express / express-serve-static-core] Fix req.is() return type
body:
The Express docs are somewhat misleading about this method. The documentation says that [`req.is()` returns `boolean`](https://expressjs.com/en/4x/api.html#req.is), but in reality, this method simply delegates to the `type-is` package, [whose return is `string | false`](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/master/types/type-is/index.d.ts#L12). I assume the Express docs are simplifying things, leaning on the fact that non-empty strings are truthy.

I've filed expressjs/expressjs.com#858 to get the Express docs fixed as well.
